releases/0/tender/title: Genetic Screening For Development Of Trees With Tolerance to Ash Dieback
releases/0/tender/description:
Contract Code
 
ecm_48079 


Title 
 
Genetic Screening For Development Of Trees With Tolerance to Ash Dieback 


Description
 
Since its discovery in 2012, ash dieback (ADB) has continued to spread throughout the UK ash population. If the UK proves similar to mainland Europe, we can expect to lose many of our ash trees over the next decade. If dying trees are to be replaced with less susceptible genotypes before the losses to industry and the ecosystem are irreversible, new tools will need to be developed. The aims of this project are to provide an Associative Transcriptomics platform to facilitate selective breeding in ash and to use this platform to develop genetic markers linked to tolerance to ADB.

releases/0/tender/title: Humber Estuary sea lamprey monitoring and tagging survey
releases/0/tender/description:
Defra procuring on behalf of Natural England: 
This project will assess the migration of adult sea lamprey Petromyzon marinus in the tidal Yorkshire Ouse. By determining when sea lamprey migrate through the tidal Ouse and which environmental factors may be impacting their migration we can gain a better understanding of these species and the potential pressures that they face. This study should determine how many sea lampreys are migrating through the catchment, how far they migrate and temporality of the migration. 

 The aim of this study is to add to the evidence gained in 2015 and increase our understanding of potential impacts of the annual DO sag on sea lamprey migration through the Humber Estuary. We hope to investigate whether sea lamprey migration occurs at the same time as the DO sag and if these two activities occur at the same time, is the DO sag causing a barrier to sea lamprey migration. 

 This study will only monitor the timing and movements of sea lamprey. Another study will be carried our concurrently by the Environment Agency (EA) who will monitor the DO levels. 

 The data collected from this study will be compared to and analysed against the DO data collected by the EA which should give us an indication of the impact of the DO sag on sea lamprey migration. This data will also be used to compare with the results and outputs from the study carried out in 2015.

releases/0/tender/description:
Chesterfield Borough Council is undertaking a project to restore part of River Doe to its original meandering channel.  Working in partnership between Chesterfield Council (landowner) and Environment Agency (main funder). 

How to Express Interest in this Tender: 

1. Register your company on the eSourcing portal (this is only required once) - Browse to the eSourcing Portal: https://in-tendhost.co.uk/noecpc and click the link to register - Enter your correct business and user details - Note: your username will be the email address you have entered - you will also then shortly receive an email confirmation. 
2. Once registered access the site and from the Home page hover over 'Tenders' on the tool bar  and select 'current tenders' from the drop down options
3. Express Interest in the tender you are interested in - Select `Express Interest` within the Tender Details ( located at the bottom of the synopsis).  On doing so, you will instantly have access to the Tender Management area for that tender.  Any available documentation will be available via the various relevant tabs.  You can access this area at any point by logging in, navigating to `My Tenders` and selecting `View Details`.
4. Responding to the tender - There will be a tab allocated to any tender stage (e.g. PQQ and/or ITT).  Under the `My Tender Return` area, you will be required to complete any mandatory questionnaires and upload any requested documentation. You can now use the `Correspondence` function to communicate with the buyer and seek any clarification (any clarifications will be found within the `Clarifications` tab). - Note the deadline for completion, then follow the onscreen instructions to complete and submit your response. - There may be a mixture of online and offline actions for you to perform (there is detailed online help available). 
You must then submit your reply using the `Submit Return` button at the bottom of the page. If you require any further assistance please consult the online help, or contact the In-tend Support Desk.  Alerts will be sent to your request email addresses when any correspondence, alterations or clarifications are issued.

The standards and criteria are available in the PQQ/ITT documents available as indicated above.

releases/0/tender/title: Quotation for the Supply of Deployable CCTV Cameras
releases/0/tender/description:
Quotation for the Supply of Deployable CCTV Cameras 

Sandwell Metropolitan Borough Council has a requirement for a number of re-deployable cameras for distribution around the six towns within the Sandwell Borough to assist with targeted crime, disorder and anti-social behaviour.

Primarily, the cameras shall be monitored via the Council’s CCTV and Concierge control room at Roway Lane in Oldbury, but shall also be capable of being monitored via Wi-Fi access from a laptop with pre-installed software.

The contract period will be for 6 months starting on 30th November 2016.  

The total estimated value excluding VAT for the duration of the contract is £80,000.

This value is based on historical spend data and is intended to be used as a guide only and is not a guarantee of the level of business that will be generated from the contract. 

The Quoted prices will remain fixed for 6 months. 

The Council will be using the In-tend e-Tendering System for this Procurement exercise, please visit https://in-tendhost.co.uk/sandwellmbc to access the Sandwell MBC In-tend Supplier Portal.

From here you will be able to register your company, express an interest in the opportunity, and gain immediate access to ITQ or other related documents.

In Order To View a On-Line Questionnaire (if applicable) or Submit a Tender, you will be required to` Opt-In`.   

Please be mindful that if you are cut and pasting your question responses onto the On-Line Questionnaire that you do so from a notepad document, this is due to the fact that some special characters are not accepted within the On-Line Questionnaire. 

For a Step by Step user guide to the Sandwell MBC In-tend Supplier Portal please click on the `Guidance for Suppliers` section of the website. All procurement responses must be carried out via the Sandwell MBC In-tend Supplier Portal.  

If you require further assistance in respect of the system please contact the In-tend support team on 0844 272 8810.

Closing date Friday 18 November 2016 at 15:00hrs

releases/0/tender/title: Portable Appliance Testing at various West Midlands Fire Service Stations and Properties
releases/0/tender/description:
In accordance with the ESPO Framework Reference: 306 Electrical Testing Service : Lot One : West Midlands Fire and Rescue Authority  (“the Authority”) is conducting this procurement for the purpose of procuring provision of the service described fully in the specification set out in Schedule 2. ( see extract below) 
The Contractor is to carry out Portable Appliance Testing (PAT) to West Midlands Fire service properties in line with the Electricity at Work Regulations 1989. For the purposes of this specification, a portable electrical appliance shall be an item of equipment which is not part of a fixed installation but is, or is intended to be, connected to a fixed installation, or a generator, by means of a flexible cable and a plug and socket. 

The Contractor shall identify each portable electrical appliance with a unique number permanently affixed to the appliance. The individual sockets of multi-socket boards/blocks and extension leads shall be individually identified. The number together with a description of the appliance shall be entered onto report forms which shall be submitted to the Facilities Management Administrator.

releases/0/tender/title: Short Breaks for Children with Disabilities.
releases/0/tender/description:
Norfolk County Council wishes to establish a framework of providers of short breaks for children with disabilities. Short Breaks allow a child to spend time apart from their parent/carer, take part in activities they like, form and develop friendships and become more confident and independent. Short Breaks allow the child’s family to have a break from the demands of caring, to relax and recharge their batteries, to spend time with each other and their other children and to reduce family stress.
There is no guarantee of business under this framework.  As a guide, the Council’s potential spend is up to £1.7 million per annum. However this does not represent a commitment to purchase the value stated, either as a minimum or a maximum, under the framework. Orders placed under the framework will be awarded on an individual basis.



Additional information: This procurement will be managed electronically via the Council`s e-procurement system. To participate in this procurement, applicants must first be registered on the system at https://in-tendhost.co.uk/norfolkcc. Full instructions for registration and use of the system can be found at https://in-tendhost.co.uk/norfolkcc/aspx/BuyerProfiles. releases/0/tender/title: Tender for the Supply and Fitting of Tyres to Cherwell District Council, South Northamptonshire Council and Oxford City Council - AWARD
releases/0/tender/description:
THE SERVICE

Cherwell District Council, South Northamptonshire Council and Oxford City Council (‘the Authorities’) are inviting Tenders for the Supply and Fitting of Tyres (the Service’) in accordance with the attached documents.

The Authorities intend to award a contract for a period of three years from 1st November 2016 with the opportunity, purely at the discretion of the Councils and in agreement with the contractor, to extend the contract by up to a further two years.  

This invitation briefly describes the Authorities’ requirements for the Service, the tendering process and the commercial terms on which the Authorities propose to contract in due course with the successful Bidder.

This Invitation also sets out details for Bidders on the form and content of Tenders which are invited and the timetable and other administrative arrangements for the tendering process.

The anticipated minimum annual expenditure between the three Authorities is £160,000 per annum, though this sum cannot be guaranteed throughout the lifetime of the contract.

The Authorities are willing to consider applications both from tyre fitting specialists with an established supply chain or directly with tyre manufacturers who have an established contract with a tyre fitting provider. In either event the contract with each Authority will be with a single contractor taking responsibility for the fulfilment of the service.

This is a competitive procurement conducted in accordance with The Public Contracts Regulations 2015 and a Contract Further details regarding the Authorities’ requirements in respect of the Service are set out in the Specification – Document 3.

Potential Additional Participants During the Lifetime of the Contract
The Authorities reserve the right to require the service provider to provide all or any part of these Service to any other Oxfordshire, Buckinghamshire or Northamptonshire local authority or other public sector partner which wishes to receive Service under the contract as follows:

•	Oxfordshire County Council
•	South Oxfordshire District Council

releases/0/tender/title: Provision of a Wheelchair Service for Dudley CCG
releases/0/tender/description:
Arden & Greater East Midlands CSU on behalf of NHS Dudley CCG is seeking expressions of interest from suitably qualified organisations for the provision of a Wheelchair Service. It is the intention of the CCG that a single contract will be awarded to the successful provider following the completion of a selection process. 

The Wheelchair service which is put in place following the procurement process will assess and provide mobility equipment to residents of the area who have long-term mobility problems.

It is the intention of the CCG that the contract put in place as a result of the procurement process will be for 3 years. 

The contracting authority intends to use an eTendering system for this procurement exercise.

Arden and Greater East Midlands CSU are managing this Procurement in accordance with the Public Contracts Regulations 2015 (the Regulations). The Services which are being procured are “Schedule 3 - Social and Other Specific Services” and Arden and Greater East Midlands CSU are bound only by those parts of the Regulations applying to Schedule 3 services. Please see published tender documentation for further detail.

Suppliers are instructed to express an interest in this tender as follows:

1.	Register your company on the eSourcing portal (this is only required once):
•	Browse to the eSourcing portal: https://ardengemcsu.bravosolution.co.uk/web/login.html and click the link to register
•	Enter your business and user details, note the username you chose and click “save” when complete
•	You will receive an e-mail with your unique password (keep this secure)
2.	Express and interest in the tender:
•	Login to the portal with your username/password
•	Click the PQQs/ITTs open to all suppliers link
•	Click on the relevant PQQ/ITT to access the content
•	Click the “Express Interest” button at the top of the page
•	This will move the PQQ/ITT into  your “My PQQs/ITTs page” (this is a secure area reserved for your projects only)
•	You can now access any attachments by clicking “Buyer Attachments” in the PQQ/ITT details box.
3.	Responding to the tender:
•	Click “my Response” under PQQ/ITT details, you can now choose to “Create Response” or “Decline to Respond” (please give a reson if declining)
•	You can now use the “Messages” function to communicate with the buyer and seek clarification
•	Note the deadline for completion, then follow the on-screen instructions to complete the PQQ/ITT
•	There may be a mixture of on-line and off-line actions for you to perform (there is detailed help available). 
•	You must the submit your response using the “Submit Response” button at the top of the page
•	If you require further assistance please consult the on-line help, or contact the eTendering help-desk on 0800 368 4850.

releases/0/tender/title: PAN1415 - LLEP Strategic Economic Plan Refresh
releases/0/tender/description:
Leicester City Council, working with the Leicester and Leicestershire Enterprise Partnership (LLEP), has awarded a contract for the provision of the LLEP Strategic Economic Plan for 2017-2022.
It is anticipated that that the plan would help provide an overview and understanding of the:
•	Leicester and Leicestershire economy and its place within regional, national and global economies.
•	Geography of the area, key projects and connectivity.
•	National and European investments in the Leicester and Leicestershire area.
•	Key projects/ interventions that help deliver jobs, housing, inward investment and value for money. 
•	Key industries seen as fundamental to the growth of the local economy. 
It is also anticipated to act as a source of evidence for businesses (and others) in and outside of the local area, that are interested in finding out more about the Leicester and Leicestershire economy.

releases/0/tender/title: NOx Abatement Programme
releases/0/tender/description:
TfL requires external support to provide NOx Abatement services to retrofit up to 5,800 diesel buses to Euro VI emission standard. This opportunity aims to deliver a Framework Agreement with six Lots for the supply, installation and maintenance of Selective Catalytic Reduction (SCR) retrofit systems. TfL requires a Framework Agreement to be put in place for a duration of 3 years with an option to extend for up to a further year. This requirement will be split into 6 Lots. These will include:
 Lot 1 – Cummins Engines (4.5 Litre)
 Lot 2 – Cummins Engines (6.7 Litre)
 Lot 3 – Mercedes Engines
Lot 4 – Scania Engines
 Lot 5 – Volvo Engines (B5)
 Lot 6 – Volvo Engines (B9)
 The contracting authority (Transport for London) is establishing this Framework Agreement on behalf of itself and other awarding bodies e.g. Bus Operators. Whilst TfL will manage the Framework Agreement, all Call Off contracts will be between the Supplier and the awarding body. 
TfL requests that any suitably experienced Supplier interested in bidding for this tender express an interest through this eTendering portal by 18/11/2016. The preliminary stage of this tender (The PQQ) must be submitted by 05/12/2016.

releases/0/tender/description:
City of Bradford Metropolitan District Council (CBMDC) provides Employee Health services and aims to be at the forefront of good practice with regards to employee health and wellbeing. 
CBMDC is looking for two Occupational health Physicians, a Primary Physician and a Secondary Physician. 
The successful bidders will work within the Employee Health and Wellbeing Service (EHWB) to support CBMDC in developing a healthy and safe working environment and encouraging people to have a positive attitude and approach to health at work. The provider will work as part of a multidisciplinary team to provide all the services as and when required to a high quality standard. EHWB provides advice, support and guidance on a wide range of occupational health and general wellbeing issues.

releases/0/tender/title: Mezzanine Floors
releases/0/tender/description:
Culham Science Centre is a 180 acre site in Oxfordshire, which is home to a large number of individual buildings occupied by the United Kingdom Atomic Energy Authority (UKAEA) which is the UK’s leading centre for Fusion research and other commercial companies to whom accommodation is leased. 

The requirement is to design, manufacture, install and commission a two storey mezzanine floor in the South end of the main hall situated in the UKAEA RACE Building (B1). The contractor is required to design and install the mezzanine in accordance with all building regulations and approvals and provide the requisite documentary evidence that the installation complies with these regulations.

The first floor mezzanine will consist of office space to accommodate up to 16 people configured as four blocks of four desks, initially in an open plan area but with the flexibility of re-configuring into four separate offices if required. There will also be a meeting room located on the East side of the mezzanine floor. The office accommodation needs to conform to building regulations.
The second floor will be a storage facility.


Please note :The award notice for this opportunity will not contain the actual value of the awarded contract (but will state an awarded value of £0 ) so as not to prejudice the legitimate commercial interests of the successful tenderer.

releases/0/tender/title: TC016 Private Hire and Hackney Carriage Vehicle Testing
releases/0/tender/description:
The Borough Council of Bolton (“the Authority”) is prepared to receive tenders for Private Hire and Hackney Carriage Vehicle Testing which will be subject to the information, specification and tender package enclosed.
The Authority has a statutory duty, provided by the Local Government (Miscellaneous Provisions) Act 1976, to ensure that all Private Hire Vehicle’s (PHV's) and Hackney Carriage Vehicle’s (HCV's) that operate within the borough’s boundaries undergo regular mechanical and bodywork compliance checks to ensure their suitability to be used as ‘taxis’ licensed by the Authority.
The Authority currently has approximately 1400 PHV’s and HCV’s licenced to operate in the borough. The majority of these will require 2 tests per year, and a proportion of tests may lead to partial or full re-tests. The Provider shall carry out Class IV MOT tests, and must have DVSA-accredited MOT testing stations within the borough’s boundary.

releases/0/tender/title: Life Coaching Services
releases/0/tender/description:
University Hospitals Birmingham NHS Foundation Trust (UHB) is inviting quotations from professional life coaches to provide life coaching services to clients of The Learning Hub as part of the Youth Promise Plus project. The life coach will be working with young people aged 17-29 who are currently not in employment, training or education (NEET) and may also come from disadvantaged backgrounds.

The Learning Hub is a purpose built training centre funded by University Hospitals Birmingham, Advantage West Midlands and European Development Funds. Its aim is to assist unemployed people within the local community back into work, by providing pre-employment training, advice and guidance. 
Youth Promise Plus is a Birmingham and Solihull Employment pathway project which provides an employer and vacancy-led approach to skills provision, responding to the needs of disadvantaged young people in the local jobs market. 

To date the Learning Hub has enabled over 2000 unemployed people to take up jobs and the successful bidder will be helping to build on this record of success by providing one to one coaching sessions to young persons enrolled on the employability programmes delivered by the Learning Hub. The purpose of these sessions will be to identify the areas the young person wishes to develop and explore any barriers that are hindering the young person from making the transition into employment, or further education and training.
     
Those wishing to submit a bid will need to do so through the Bravo e-tendering portal   

The contracting authority considers that this contract may be suitable for economic operators that are small or medium enterprises (SMEs). However, any selection of bidders will be based solely on the criteria set out for the procurement.

releases/0/tender/description:
The Houses of Parliament wish to procure woven carpets, incorporating customised patterns, to conduct scheduled maintenance and repairs to existing floor coverings in place, and their due replacement where required. These areas will include offices, and some rooms and corridors subject to high levels of footfall. The patterns of these woven carpets must harmonise with and be compatible with the existing floorcoverings for consistency during installation.  Whilst the main focus of this tender is the provision of a bulk orders of 80% wool, 20% nylon woven carpets, it has been decided that the woven carpet range should also include a quantity of synthetic woven floorcoverings (60% to 100% nylon) to maximise our ability to carry out pest control measures.

To ensure value for money, the quality required should ensure that the products remain in operational use beyond any minimum warranty period, regardless of works scheduled during their natural lifecycle; the ability to lift and store the material is essential.  The estimated value of the framework includes the bulk purchase and delivery of woven carpets over the period of the framework, and their installation.

releases/0/tender/title: 15 006 Lifelong Learning - Adult Education Budget
releases/0/tender/description:
Cheshire East Lifelong Learning (CE LL) is undertaking a commissioning exercise to set up an approved supplier list for the procurement of Adult Education Budget Provision for the residents of the Borough.

CE LL is funded as the lead body for Adult Education Budget provision and will be sub-contracting work under this funding stream.  Providers will need to meet the eligibility criteria outlined in the service specification in order to be considered for the list.

The approved supplier list will be split into lots as below:
Lot 1 Adult Education Budget Provision: Accredited Learning
Lot 2 Adult Education Budget Provision: Health and Wellbeing Programmes (Non-accredited learning)
Lot 3 Adult Education Budget Provision: Taster/Engagement Programmes (Non-accredited learning)
Lot 4 Adult Education Budget Provision: Longer programmes leading to Employment Outcomes (Non-accredited learning)
Lot 5 (+) - Additional lots may be added throughout the life of the approved supplier list (to be advised at a later date should the need arise).

A proportion of the funding will be targeted at the 19+ age group who face challenges securing sustainable employment.  The non-accredited learning will focus on turning around the lives of local people and maximising the impact of public funding on the social and economic wellbeing of individuals, families and communities with a strong focus on those who are most disadvantaged.

A proportion of funding will be accredited learning and will be focused on unemployed individuals within the Borough who are eligible for full funding as outlined in the service specification. Commissioned provision will be aimed at entry level to level 2.  This learning will be targeted at meeting local wellbeing and employment priorities in a number of subject areas.

The approved supplier list will be opened via The Chest a minimum of 3 times per year so that new providers can join the list.  Being accepted onto the list is no guarantee of any volume of work.  Potential Provider's who fail to get onto the list may re-apply to join a maximum of 3 times.

Cheshire East Council reserves the right to negotiate on aspects of providers bids post acceptance onto the list and prior to any contract award based on the call off criteria laid out in the service specification.    

The budget is a maximum of £495K per year across all lots.
